{"content":"---\ntitle: \"Compiler Error CS0822 | Microsoft Docs\"\n\nms.date: \"2015-07-20\"\nms.prod: .net\n\n\nms.technology: \n  - \"devlang-csharp\"\n\nms.topic: \"article\"\nf1_keywords: \n  - \"CS0822\"\ndev_langs: \n  - \"CSharp\"\nhelpviewer_keywords: \n  - \"CS0822\"\nms.assetid: 519091be-2332-4df4-acd9-e3b633966b3d\ncaps.latest.revision: 7\nauthor: \"BillWagner\"\nms.author: \"wiwagn\"\n\ntranslation.priority.ht: \n  - \"de-de\"\n  - \"es-es\"\n  - \"fr-fr\"\n  - \"it-it\"\n  - \"ja-jp\"\n  - \"ko-kr\"\n  - \"ru-ru\"\n  - \"zh-cn\"\n  - \"zh-tw\"\ntranslation.priority.mt: \n  - \"cs-cz\"\n  - \"pl-pl\"\n  - \"pt-br\"\n  - \"tr-tr\"\n---\n# Compiler Error CS0822\nImplicitly typed locals cannot be const  \n  \n Implicitly typed local variables are only necessary for storing anonymous types. In all other cases they are just a convenience. If the value of the variable never changes, just give it an explicit type. Attempting to use the `readonly` modifier with an implicitly typed local will generate CS0106.  \n  \n## To correct this error  \n  \n1.  If you require the variable to be constant or `readonly`, give it an explicit type.  \n  \n## Example  \n The following code generates CS0822:  \n  \n```  \n// cs0822.cs  \nclass A  \n{  \n  \n    public static int Main()  \n    {  \n        const var x = 0; // CS0822.cs  \n        return -1;  \n    }  \n}  \n```  \n  \n## See Also  \n [Implicitly Typed Local Variables](../../csharp/programming-guide/classes-and-structs/implicitly-typed-local-variables.md)","nodes":[{"pos":[12,50],"content":"Compiler Error CS0822 | Microsoft Docs","needQuote":false,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"Compiler Error CS0822 | Microsoft Docs","pos":[0,38]}]},{"pos":[565,586],"content":"Compiler Error CS0822","linkify":"Compiler Error CS0822","nodes":[{"content":"Compiler Error CS0822","pos":[0,21]}]},{"content":"Implicitly typed locals cannot be const","pos":[587,626]},{"content":"Implicitly typed local variables are only necessary